									<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
										<tr>
											<td width="100%" valign="top">					
												<!-- START NEWS AREAS-->
												<table width="90%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
													<tr><td valign="top" width="100%">&nbsp;<br>
													<!-- strMainData goes here-->
													<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='header' bgcolor='black' width='100%'>PALADIN STRATEGIES AND PLAYGUIDES</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='spti'>DWARVEN PALADINS, A WALK THRU </font> - <small>Hardolek, The Nameless</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>   Hail all, Hardolek the hard-arse coming to you with bits and nuggets of information that might just help you to furthering xp and levels. I've been a dwarven paladin for 17 seasons now and I've gathered up a mountain of data and I'd like to pass it on to the next holy warrior of Norrath, notice I did not specify race--meaning I believe any paladin could use this info. 

   1st off, don't do like I did. I put bonus points into wisdom and intelligence...albeit I may be smarter than most dwarves...I'm not as battle conditioned as the rest. I should have placed a majority of my extra points into agility, but I didn't and I'm paying for it now! Put 10 in, then put 5 into strength and flip a coin. Heads, dexterity; tails, more agility. Dwarves have terrible agility (found that out too late!) so the more the better! Now this advice is for fellow dwarves who wish to become holy warriors...erudites, humans, and 1/2 elves who want to become paladins should consult the paladin creation guide for the right stats to place extra points for said race you want.

Next and this is the most important, fight near the guards and don't get in over your head! 

"How do I know if I'm over my head ?" you ask? 

   Well, if your life bar disentigrates after a few blows or you have three to seven mobs on your tail , you're in over your head! One way to alleviate this problem is to con EVERYTHING! Your a tank early on so green/blues are what you should fight and to some degree evens, but not without a few guidelines on evens early on:

1) Always have Lay on Hands ready. Make sure it's recharged and ready to save yer arse!
2) Make sure you can make a b-line to guards if things get to hairy, i.e.- Post LoH and you're still losing hit points badly!
3) DON'T, I repeat DON'T try and fight evens out of a camp area (like the goblin camps throughout Butcherblock Mountains), if another Mob re-spawns in mid-battle...you can kiss your arse good-bye for the most part!

    Following these easy guidelines and you should have relatively great luck with Mobs. My first death was at level 7, in Befallen (and yes, they came quite frequently after that too LOL). If you use your noodle too, who knows when your first death will come, if ever =)

   Now you ask, "Where can I fight to get the promised land ?"

   The promised land is level 9 by the way, just stick to newbie area mobs; turn 4 Runnyeye warbeads to the warrior guildmaster for xp, 4 unstacked bonechips to Gunlok Jure, who's outside the paladin guild, 4 skunk scent glands to the one of the dwarf clerics, 4 aviak chick talons to the guy INSIDE the paladin guild, do the scarab armour quests in front of the warrior guild...boots and helm, good luck finding a pristine scarab shell though! Go into the mine shaft and kill giant rats, turn in 4 unstackable pelts to one of the dwarf warrior guildmasters (notice again, these are for dwarves, other paladins have newbie quests for their race as well. Just hail everybody and follow key words to get info from NPCs) The xp from the mobs plus the quest reward xp should help ye get to level 9. When you get your  spells, you should be able to tackle a few spots in Buthcherblock. The goblin camps should be nice and juicy xp, but are aways from guards so be careful! Oh yeah, keep an eye out fer the two ogres that roam BB, their paired heads get you Bloodforge armour (watchout fer the female, she's a shaman & will mess you up!) You could head into Greater Faydark...and find groups for Crushbone Orcs on orc hill or inside the citadel itself, just stay near the zone point because orc trains are deadly at that level. When I reached 15 I thought, hehe watch out undead, cuz I could get ward undead. Well I failed to remember to utilize my own wisdom and got in over my head fighting undead. The chessboard becomes a major source of xp around that level with blue/even and some yellow undead pawns, watch out fer the undead rooks...heavy hitters, undead bishops...nasty necros, and undead kings...a wizard, I believe. At 16 I ventured to Befallen, didn't quite make it to 17 though. But I made my way to Highpass Hold and leveled up REAL quick! The xp in HH is unbelievable at this point and I'm going to try and stay and get the rare spawned loot from there:
-Polished granite tomahawk
-Cracked Darkwood Shield
(both off of the gnoll side)
-Shiny Brass Halberd
-Shralock pack
(from the orc side)

Well, I've ranted enough now. I should mention a few more things before I go though. Try to obtain banded armour as soon as possible, then bronze...heavy yes, but better armour class makes up fer it. Try and save some platinum for a magic weapon...one hand? Two hand? Pick the one YOU like best...I'm a sword and shield man myself (2-hnders take too long!) and if that's the route save some pp for the shiny brass shield...some undead are magic weapon only and normal shields won't let you bash with them. 

     I'm only level 17 now, but a surname is on the horizen fer me. If you play your cards right and have a bit of luck...you'll pass me before you know it!
(I guarentee it! I only play a few hours a day so I know you'll pass me eventually!)

Hardolek, dwarven paladin of the 17th season</td></tr>
